        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-01-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-01-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="15" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d15">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–1847: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-01-18">January 18,
                            1947</date>.<lb/>[Received January 18—1:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. Communist delegation leader Wang Ping-nan called on me this morning to state
                    that reply had been received from Yenan that if Government accepts Communists’
                    two demands (abolition of National Assembly and Constitution and return to
                    military position of January 13, 1946) Communist Party would immediately send
                    delegation to Nanking to resume negotiations and that there was no need to send
                    Government emissaries to Yenan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
